# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ashburton-lakes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] The **2013 New Zealand census** was the thirty-third national census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] "The National Census Day" used for the census was on Tuesday, 5 March 2013.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] The population of New Zealand was counted as 4,242,048 – an increase of 214,101 or 5.3% over the 2006 census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] The 2013 census forms were the same as those developed for the 2011 census which was cancelled due to the major February 2011 earthquake in Christchurch.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] New Zealand's next census was conducted in March 2018.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] The results from the post-enumeration survey showed that the 2013 census recorded 97.6 percent of the residents in New Zealand on census night.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] However, the overall response rate was 92.9 percent, with a non-response rate of 7.1 percent made up of the net undercount and people who were counted in the census but had not received a form.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] Population counts for New Zealand regions.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] Note: All figures are for the census usually resident population count.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] The census usually resident population count of 4,242,048 included 230,649 people without an ethnic response and 4,011,399 people who identified with at least one ethnicity.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] The figures for the total ethnicity of the population.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] The number of people living in New Zealand who were born overseas continued to climb.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] The table below is based on religious affiliation data recorded at the last three censuses for usually resident people.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2013-new-zealand-census] Figures and percentages may not add to 100 percent as people can state more than one religion.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] The **2018 New Zealand census**, which took place on Tuesday 6 March 2018, was the thirty-fourth national census in New Zealand.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] The population of New Zealand was counted as 4,699,755 – an increase of 457,707 (10.79%) over the 2013 census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Results from the 2018 census were released to the public on 23 September 2019, from the Statistics New Zealand website.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] The most recent New Zealand census was held in March 2023.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] The *Census Act 1877* required censuses to be held every fifth year and is well embedded in legislation and government systems.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Since 1881, censuses have been held every five years, with the exceptions of those in 1931 and 1941 and the one in 2011 which was cancelled due to the February 2011 earthquake in Christchurch, which displaced many Canterbury residents from their homes only a few weeks before census day.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] It was rescheduled for March 2013, so the 2013 census is the previous census completed before this one.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] In July 2018, it was estimated that the 2018 census had a "full or partial" response for 90 percent of individuals, down from 94.5 percent in the 2013 census and the planned release date for census information was changed from October of the same year to March 2019.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] This drop, which already amounted to the lowest census response rate for fifty years, was blamed on a 'digital-first' policy for the census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] An independent review was initiated by the Government Statistician in October 2019, and in November Statistics NZ announced that release of census data would be pushed back to at least April 2019 due to "the complex nature of the task".
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] In early April 2019, the Government Statistician, Liz MacPherson was facing possible charges of contempt of parliament.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] She had twice refused, on 13 February and in early April, to disclose the number of partially and fully completed responses.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] On 9 April, she reported that one in seven New Zealanders, 700,000 people, failed to complete the census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Due to a decision to conduct the census primarily online, the census attracted only an 83% response rate, even lower than the 90% earlier reported, and well short of the 94% census percent target and a nine percent drop from the previous 2013 New Zealand census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Statistics New Zealand annually conducts population projections for New Zealand as a whole, which are based on data from the previous census (in this case, the 2013 census) and calculated using a cohort-component method.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Population projections also take into consideration births, deaths, and net migration.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] In 2016, New Zealand's population at the time of the 2018 census was projected to be between 4,807,000 and 4,944,000.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Data uses fixed random rounding to protect confidentiality; each data point is rounded either to the nearest multiple of 3 (2⁄3 chance) or the next-nearest multiple of 3 (1⁄3 chance).
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] The census usually-resident population count of New Zealand is a count of all people who usually live in and were present in the country on census night (6 March 2018), and excludes overseas visitors and New Zealand residents who are temporarily overseas.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Due to the high rate of non-response in the census, the published results combine answers from census forms with data from the 2013 Census and from government administrative data.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Reports from an External Data Quality Review Panel include quality ratings for each variable, taking the added data into account.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Population counts for regions of New Zealand.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] All figures are for the census usually-resident population count.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is for the census's usually-resident population.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] There was no change in the top five ethnicities between the 2013 and 2018 censuses, which are New Zealand European (64.1%), Māori (16.5%), Chinese (4.9%), Indian (4.7%), and Samoan (3.9%).
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is for the census usually-resident population count.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Results add up to over 100% due to people declaring multiple ethnicities.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Most New Zealanders, 48.5% of the population, identify as being irreligious.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] The vast majority of New Zealanders, 95.4%, speak English; in second place is Māori, with 4.0% of the population being able to speak it.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] New Zealanders who declare Māori descent.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] 18.5% of New Zealanders have at least some Māori descent.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] The largest age group is people aged 25 to 29, who comprise 7.3% of the population.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is the census usually-resident population count.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is for the census usually-resident population count of people aged 15 years and over.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2018-new-zealand-census] Data is for the census usually-resident population count of employed people aged 15 years and over.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The **2023 New Zealand census**, which took place on 7 March 2023, was the thirty-fifth national census in New Zealand.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] It implemented measures that aimed to increase the Census' effectiveness in response to the issues faced with the 2018 census, including supporting Māori to complete the census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] It also included new questions on topics such as gender, sexual identity, and disabilities/health conditions.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The population of New Zealand was counted as 4,993,923 – an increase of (6.26%) over the 2018 census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The first Census data was published on 29 May 2024, in a range of data products and services.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The 2023 census can be completed online or on paper forms.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Forms with an access code were mailed out to householders from 20 February, but paper forms could be requested online or by telephone.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The telephone number had operators speaking English, te reo Māori, Samoan, Tongan, Korean, Mandarin, Cantonese, Hindi, and Punjabi.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] New Zealand Sign Language was available through NZ Relay.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] One dwelling form was required for each household, and one individual form was required for each person present in the dwelling on Tuesday 7 March 2023.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The first full census in New Zealand was conducted in 1851, and the census was triennial until 1881, at which time it became five-yearly.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The 1931 census was cancelled due to the effects of the Great Depression, as was the 1941 census due to World War II.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The 1946 census was brought forward to Tuesday 25 September 1945, so that the results could be used for an electoral redistribution (the first for ten years) before the 1946 election.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] 1951 was the first year in which Māori and European New Zealanders were treated equally, with European New Zealanders having had a different census form in previous years and separate censuses in the nineteenth century.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Results for those censuses before 1966 have been destroyed with a few exceptions and those since will not be available before 2066.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The 2006 census was held on Tuesday, 7 March.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] For the first time, respondents had the option of completing their census form online rather than by a printed form.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The 2011 census was scheduled for Tuesday, 8 March.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] However, due to the Christchurch earthquake on 22 February 2011, it was cancelled.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] For the first time ever, all 2011 census forms would have been digitally archived.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] On 27 May 2011 Statistics New Zealand announced that a census would take place in March 2013.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The legislation required to change the census date was introduced to Parliament in August 2011.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The 2013 census was held on Tuesday 5 March 2013 and the 2018 census was held on Tuesday 6 March 2018.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The 2018 census faced wide criticism for low response rates, a poor rollout of the online component of the census and delays.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] This resulted in an independent review of the census process, and the resignation of the then-Chief Executive of Statistics New Zealand Liz MacPherson.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The date for the 2023 New Zealand census was announced by Stats NZ on 28 September 2022.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] In February 2023, Cyclone Gabrielle had devastated parts of the North Island, prompting the Government to declare a national state of emergency in six regions.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] To address the disruption caused by Cyclone Gabrielle, the Government had agreed to an eight-week extension of the census for the worst affected areas.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] People living in cyclone-affected areas including the Far North District, Gisborne District, and Hawkes Bay had until 1 June to complete their Census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] In addition, Statistics New Zealand asked the Government for an extra NZ$37 million to cover extra costs.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Face-to-face visits were also delayed in some affected areas.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Field operations in Gisborne and Hawkes Bay commenced on 3 April.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] On 6 March 2023, Radio New Zealand reported that just one million New Zealanders had filled out their census forms.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Statistics New Zealand's deputy chief executive census and collections operation, Simon Mason, described the response as underwhelming and attributed the lower response rate to the disruption caused by Cyclone Gabrielle and opposition by some on social media to participating in the census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] In response to criticism of the 2018 New Zealand census, Mason confirmed that Statistics NZ had sent two forms in the post to bolster public engagement.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] By 31 March, Statistics NZ had confirmed that four million people had returned their census forms; beating the 30 April milestone for the 2018 census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] On 5 April, *Newsroom* reported that one in five people had not returned their census forms, with the figure rising to two in five people within the Māori and Pacific communities.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] *Newsroom* also reported low rates of participation in Gisborne and Hawkes Bay; with 26,200 out of Gisborne's estimated total population of 52,100 and 89,300 out of Hawkes Bay's population of 182,700 returning their survey forms.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] According to *Newsroom*, Statistics NZ had fallen behind its target of visiting all non-responding and partially responding households by nine days after 7 March.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] By 31 March, 29,000 dwellings outside Te Mana Whakatipu, Gisborne, and Hawkes Bay had not received their first visit.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Mason also confirmed that census workers had made 1.3 million non-response follow-up visits to 790,000 dwellings by 31 March.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] In an effort to boost participation, Statistics NZ deployed over 3,000 census collectors in the community until 3 May and until 1 June in Hawkes Bay and Gisborne.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Mason also confirmed that Statistics NZ would focus on supporting under-represented groups including Māori.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] By 20 April, Statistics NZ confirmed that 4.3 million people had returned their census forms while one in five respondents had not returned their forms.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The *Bay of Plenty Times* reported that 274,300 had returned their forms by 19 April.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] However, 73,400 forms had not been returned; with 37,300 of these non-respondents being Māori and 17,700 being youths.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Non-respondents face a NZ$2,000 fine under the Data and Statistics Act 2022.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] By 1 May, Statistics NZ confirmed that 4,408,894 people out of an estimated population of 5.15 million had returned their census forms.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Statistics NZ spokesperson Tracy Dillimore confirmed that the national Census response rate was 86%.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Deputy government statistician Simon Mason warned that people who had not completed their census forms would receive a final notice from 9 May.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] National Party statistics spokesperson Simon Watts described the 2023 Census as a failure and doubted that Statistics NZ would reach its 90% target.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Watts also disputed Statistic NZ's position that Cyclone Gabrielle had disrupted the census collection process, pointing out that most of the uncompleted forms were from major cities with lower completion rates among Māori and Pasifika.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Watts estimated that the 2023 Census would cost NZ$337 million, including the extra NZ$37 million requested by Statistics NZ.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] By contrast, the Minister of Statistics Deborah Russell claimed that the 2023 Census was an improvement over the 2018 Census, citing the former's 86% response rate in comparison with the latter's overall response rate of 81.6%.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] By 20 May, 4.5 million census forms (covering 88% of the population) had been returned.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] According to Deputy Government Statistician Simon Mason, 55,000 final notice packs had been sent to non-responding households.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] At the time, 25% of Māori and Pasifika had not returned their census forms.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] During the 2023 census, Te Whānau-ā-Apanui trialled a "by Māori, for Māori" census collection drive in East Cape, Gisborne District and parts of the Northland Region.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Data Iwi Leaders Forum spokesperson Rahui Papa credited the "by Māori, for Māori" drive with ensuring a 90% Māori uptake in the East Cape.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The party's candidate Takutai Tarsh Kemp had won the Tāmakai Makaurau seat during the 2023 election.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] A whistleblower from the Ministry of Social Development had alerted Statistics NZ and the Police, which had delayed investigating the matter.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] In response, Te Pāti Māori leader John Tamihere denied the allegations and claimed they were made by disgruntled former staff.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Tamihere said that the marae had been working with the Whānau Ora Commissioning Agency to promote Māori participation in the 2023 census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Tamihere also acknowledged that marae workers had given gifts to encourage people to participate in the 2023 Census and switch to the Māori roll.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Prime Minister Christopher Luxon said the allegations are "pretty serious" and they need to be investigated promptly but were an issue for the party and the authorities.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] David Seymour said a ministerial inquiry could be warranted and Leader of the Opposition Chris Hipkins said the allegations were "very serious" and warranted a "rigorous and very credible" review.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Doug Craig was appointed to investigate the census data misuse allegations.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The findings will be shared with the New Zealand Police who are also investigating.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] On 27 August 2024, former academic Rawiri Taonui claimed that the whistleblowers connected to Destiny Church had instigated the allegations against Manurewa Marae and Te Pāti Māori following a failed attempt by the church to take over the marae.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] On 22 January 2025, Statistics New Zealand's investigation cleared the Whanau Ora Commissioning Agency of data breaches during the 2023 Census, finding that the agency increased Māori participation.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The report made nine recommendations to improve Statistics NZ's procedures and referred allegations against Manurewa Marae to the Privacy Commissioner.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The report also found no evidence that one of the alleged whistleblowers had attempted to contact Statistics NZ regarding allegations against the marae.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] On 11 February 2025, *The New Zealand Herald* reported that Detective Superintendent Ross McKay was leading an investigation into allegations regarding Te Pāti Māori's misuse of census data and Covid-19 vaccination information at Manurewa Marae during the 2023 general election.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The first results from the census were released on 29 May 2024.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Many respondents identify with multiple ancestries.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Outputting data on multiple ethnicities is normally handled one of two ways: total response or prioritised ethnicity.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] For this list, the total response method is used.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Total response counts people of multiple ethnicities in each ethnic groups in which they identify.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] While this shows all the people that identify with a particular ethnicities, the sum of all ethnic group populations adds to more than the total population.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] For example, a person who identifies as New Zealand European and Māori would be counted twice, once under each ethnicity, under total response output.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Prioritised ethnicity counts people with multiple ethnicities in the highest-priority single ethnic group in which they identify.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The order of priority for ethnicity, from highest to lowest, is Māori, Pacific peoples, Asian, MELAA, other and European.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] While it has the advantage that the sum of all ethnic groups equals the total population, the preferential order can cause ethnic groups to be overrepresented or underrepresented, and may categorise a person differently from their self-identified primary ethnicity.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] For example, a person who identifies as New Zealand European and Māori would be counted under the Māori ethnic group under prioritised ethnicity output.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] The median age was 38.1 years, up from 37.4 years at the 2018 census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] In June 2025, Statistics New Zealand released new figures from the 2023 Census showing that 86,000 people moved from the North Island to the South Island between 2018 and 2023.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] During that same period, 30,000 people migrated from the South Island to the North Island.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] New census questions allowed data to be gathered for the first time on, among others, the LGBTIQ+ population.
[src:ashburton-lakes/2023-new-zealand-census] Data found that 1 in 20 adults identified as LGBTIQ+.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] The station was originally launched on 873 AM frequency as a local station operated by the government owned Radio New Zealand, the station was originally branded as its callsign 3ZE.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] The station operated out of the second floor of the former Loan Society Building on Tancred Street, before moving across the road to Highgate House in the early 1990s.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] In July 1996 the New Zealand Government sold off the commercial arm of Radio New Zealand, the sale included 3ZE.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] The new owner was The Radio Network, a subsidiary of APN News & Media and Clear Channel Communications, which operated as a division of the Australian Radio Network.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] In 1998 The Radio Network grouped all their local stations in smaller markets together to form the Community Radio Network.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] 3ZE continued to run a local breakfast show between 6 am and 10 am but outside breakfast all stations part of the Community Radio Network took network programming from a central studio based in Taupo.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] The station added an FM frequency which improved reception and suited the inclusion of a significant amount of music within its programme, becoming 92.5 3ZE FM.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] 3ZE's AM frequency is now used to re-broadcast Newstalk ZB.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] On December 1, 2000 the Community Radio Network was discontinued and all stations become part of the Classic Hits FM network, as a result 3ZE was rebranded as Classic Hits 92.5 ZEFM.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] The station continued to run a local breakfast but now outside breakfast all programming originated from the Classic Hits studios in Auckland.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] In the early 2010s the station moved to the newly redeveloped Somerset House.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] On April 28, 2014 all stations part of the Classic Hits network were rebranded as The Hits.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] A networked breakfast presented by Polly Gillespie and Grant Kareama was introduced to almost all The Hits stations with the former breakfast announcer moved to present a 6-hour show between 9 am and 3 pm.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] At this stage breakfast presenter, Phill Hooper, was moved to the 9 am-3 pm timeslot.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] When the station was branded from Classic Hits to The Hits feedback from local listeners in the Ashburton region was not positive, both with the removal of the local breakfast and change in music format.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] A decision was made later in 2014 to network Gore based radio station Hokonui into the Ashburton market using the 92.5FM frequency and have Phill Hooper present a local breakfast on this station to Ashburton listeners.
[src:ashburton-lakes/3ze] The Hits remains in the Ashburton region on 89.3FM running total network programming.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Like other species in the family Apiaceae, speargrasses have taproots and small flowers, which are clustered into inflorescences called umbels.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Species can be distinguished by size, habit, flower head and bract size and shape, leaf shape, and the type of stipules growing at the leaf base.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Speargrasses in the *A. aurea* group (six species and three tag-named taxa) have milky sap, while most other species have clear sap.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Aciphylla is dioecious, with separate male and female plants which do not flower every year.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Because of this, identifying plants to species can depend on leaf characters and locality.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] The seeds of *Aciphylla* are winged schizocarps dispersed by the wind.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Many species of speargrass have tough, rigid leaves and flower bracts tipped with long sharp spikes, arranged in one or more rosettes which present spines in every direction.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] This is reflected in the name of the genus: *Aci* (needle) *phylla* (leaf).
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] This form is hypothesised to have evolved to deter browsing by birds: the extinct giant moa.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Long spines are known to deter ratite birds from browsing other plants, and the two large-leaved species endemic to the Chatham Islands, which never had moa, have soft leaves without spikes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Around 45–52 species of *Aciphylla* are recognised, along with forms known only by informal tag names, which may or may not represent distinct species.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] All but two species of *Aciphylla* are confined to New Zealand; the remaining two are endemic to Australia.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Most species live in or near the alpine zone, but they range from mountains to coast.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] The group reaches its highest diversity in the South Island.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Māori on occasion plaited sandals out of *Aciphylla* leaves for travel over snowy terrain.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] More important, though, was the aromatic gum extracted from the leaves, used in scented oils and sachets.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Collecting taramea resin was traditionally the work of women.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] It was collected by cutting or burning plants in the evening, and gathering the exuded gum (called *pia*) in the morning.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Leaves could also be gathered, plaited, and heated over several days to force out the gum into a gourd.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] The process was tapu, and only young girls collected the pia after appropriate karakia (prayers) had been performed.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Anyone collecting gum needed to sleep with their knees drawn up, in a crouching position, for if they slept in the ordinary way the gum would sink to the roots instead of rising.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] The collected oil hardened into a resin, *ware-taramea*, or could be mixed with animal fat (from kererū, tītī, weka, tūī, or kiore) to preserve the fragrance.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] It was worn in a pouch next to the skin known as a *hei-taramea*, used to dress the hair, or rubbed directly on the body.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] It could also be stored in a hollow bone or bunch of feathers, and when warmed by body heat gave off a pleasant fragrance.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] The aromatic gum could be stored in a gourd or shell, and was a valuable trade good and gift.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Taramea perfume is still prepared commercially by Ngāi Tahu, using a steam extraction method on hand-harvested leaves.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] *A. aurea* contains the non-volatile polyacetylene falcarindiol and the seeds contained steam-distilled volatiles such as heptanal and octanoic acid.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Many *Aciphylla* species are threatened by introduced mammals, such as domestic sheep, hares (which can eat the leaves from the side to avoid the spiny tips), and feral pigs (which will dig up plants to eat the carrot-like taproot).
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] The decline of *A. colensoi* due to browsing from rabbits was noted as early as 1883.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Widespread conversion of the New Zealand high country for sheep farming and pasture is also a threat to the group.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] In the Chatham Islands, *Aciphylla dieffenbachii* is the sole host of another endangered flightless weevil, *Hadramphus spinipennis* or coxella weevil.
[src:ashburton-lakes/aciphylla] Both weevil and its host are threatened by browsing mammals.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] Rakaia was also the junction of the Methven Branch, a branch line railway to Methven that operated from 1880 until its closure in 1976.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] An accident at the railway station in 1899 killed four people.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] Rakaia's most obvious feature is a large fibreglass salmon.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The river from which the town takes its name is known for its salmon fishing and jetboating.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] In 2025 the sculpture was temporarily moved to the workshop of its creator Phil Price for restoration.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The town and river were previously known as *Cholmondeley*, but the Māori name would eventually prevail over the English one.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The rural community of Acton is located south of the Rakaia township.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] Rakaia is described by Statistics New Zealand as a small urban area and covers 11.30 km2 (4.36 sq mi) and had an estimated population of 1,680 as of June 2025, with a population density of 148.7 people per km2.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] Rakaia had a population of 1,440 at the 2018 New Zealand census, an increase of 168 people (13.2%) since the 2013 census, and an increase of 369 people (34.5%) since the 2006 census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] There were 576 households, comprising 723 males and 720 females, giving a sex ratio of 1.0 males per female.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] Ethnicities were 86.9% European/Pākehā, 12.9% Māori, 5.2% Pasifika, 3.3% Asian, and 1.7% other ethnicities.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] People may identify with more than one ethnicity.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The percentage of people born overseas was 12.3, compared with 27.1% nationally.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] Although some people chose not to answer the census's question about religious affiliation, 53.1% had no religion, 34.8% were Christian, 0.6% had Māori religious beliefs, 0.4% were Hindu, 0.2% were Muslim, 0.6% were Buddhist and 1.9% had other religions.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] Of those at least 15 years old, 93 (8.2%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, and 330 (29.0%) people had no formal qualifications.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The median income was $33,500, compared with $31,800 nationally.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The employment status of those at least 15 was that 636 (55.9%) people were employed full-time, 162 (14.2%) were part-time, and 24 (2.1%) were unemployed.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] It was designed by architect Benjamin Mountfort in a Gothic style.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] It is considered a typical example of the wooden churches he designed for small parishes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The church was listed as a category two historic place in 1992.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The Rakaia Post Office was built in 1910.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The Rakaia Bank of New Zealand building.
[src:ashburton-lakes/acton-new-zealand] The South Rakaia Hotel is almost 150 years old.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] An **administrative centre** is a seat of regional administration or local government, or a county seat or town, or the place where the central administration of a commune or equivalent subdivision, is located.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In countries with French as an administrative language, such as Belgium, Luxembourg, Switzerland and many African countries, a ***chef-lieu*** (French pronunciation: [ʃɛfljø], pl.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] 'chief place' or 'main place') is a town or city that is important from an administrative perspective.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The capitals of Algerian provinces, districts, and communes are called *chefs-lieux*.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* in Belgium is the administrative centre of each of the ten provinces of Belgium.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Three of these cities also give their name to their province (Antwerp, Liège and Namur).
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of a French department is known as the prefecture (*préfecture*).
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] This is the town or city where the prefect of the department (and all services under their control) are situated, in a building also known as the prefecture.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In every French region, one of the departments has preeminence over the others, and the prefect carries the title of *préfet de la région* (lit.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] 'Prefect of the Region') or *préfet du département* (lit.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] 'Prefect of the Department') and the city where the regional prefect is found is known as the *chef-lieu* of the region.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The services are, however, controlled by the prefecture of the department.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of an arrondissement, commonly known as the *sous-préfecture* is the city or town where the sub-prefect of the arrondissement (and the services directly under their control) are situated, in a building called the sub-prefecture.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The arrondissement where the department prefecture is located does not normally have a sub-prefect or sub-prefecture, the administration being devolved usually to the secretary-general of the departmental prefecture, who functions as sub-prefect for the arrondissement.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of a canton is usually the biggest city or town within the canton, but has only a nominal role.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] No specific services are controlled by it.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In past decades, there was always a gendarmerie, a treasurer and a justice of the peace.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* indicates the principal city of the provinces of New Caledonia.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] So Nouméa is the chef-lieu of South Province.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] But the chef-lieu can also mean the principal area within a town.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] So Wé is part of the town of Lifou, but is the chef-lieu of Lifou.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In the Loyalty Islands and the other islands, the name of the chef-lieu differs from that of the name of the town.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] For the towns of the mainland, the chef-lieu has the same name as the town.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Nouméa is a town composed only of Nouméa.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Many of the West African states which gained independence from France in the mid-20th century also inherited the French administrative structure of departments and communes, headed by a *chef-lieu*.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] States still using *chef-lieu* to identify the administrative headquarters of a government subdivision include Senegal, Burkina Faso, Benin, Mali, and Niger.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Taking Niger and Mali as examples, the administrative subdivisions down to the commune level each have a formal place of administrative headquarters, titled the *chef-lieu*.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The larger portion of the terminology of administrative division is inherited from colonial rule as part of French West Africa, and has survived and been somewhat modified over time.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In both nations there have been remarkably parallel histories.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Since decentralization began in both nations in the 1990s, the *chef-lieu* transitioned from the location of the governor, commandant, or prefect and their staff to the location of the commune, cercle, department, and regional councils and a variety of decentralized bodies.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The **chef-lieu** of a region, cercle or department is usually also a communal **chef-lieu**.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Both nations also established a supreme council of local government authorities (*Haut conseil des collectivités territoriales*) seated at the nation's capital.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Smaller subdivisions in Mali's communes (villages, tribal councils, and quarters) are administered from a *place* (lit.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] 'site'), so the *chef-lieu* is literally the 'chief-place' even at the lowest level.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In Jordan, the administrative centres are known as chief towns or *nahias*.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Nahias may be in charge of a sub-district (*qda*), a district (*liwa*), or a governorate (*muhafazah*).
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Luxembourg is divided into four electoral constituencies, twelve cantons, as well as 100 communes (Luxembourgish: *Gemengen*).
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Cantons have each a *chef-lieu* and are named after it.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The same is true for each commune which is composed of more than one town or village.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Usually, with a few exceptions, the commune is named after the communal *chef-lieu*.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In Russia, several million-plus cities in federal districts have the official status of an administrative centre: Moscow (as the main city of the Central Federal District), Vladivostok, Volgograd, Yekaterinburg, Nizhny Novgorod, Novosibirsk, Pyatigorsk, Rostov-on-Don and St.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The main cities of regions and municipal districts are also called unofficially the administrative centre or simply the centre.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The only exception to this rule is the republics, for which the term "capital" is used to refer to the seat of government.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The capital of Russia is also an entity to which the term "administrative centre" does not apply.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In Sweden there are two levels of administrative centre; the local municipal and the regional county.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Central locality (Swedish: *centralort*) is a term commonly ascribed to the settlement that serves as a municipal administrative centre.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] This level handles the local administrative and political tasks of the surrounding settlements.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Since central place theory was the guiding principle during the 1962–1977 municipal reform, most municipalities were dominated by a larger urban area where the political seat was located.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Most municipalities are named for their central locality, but there are several exceptions.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] There are many deviations from the central locality principle.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Some municipalities are dominated by two or more towns of similar size, and sometimes they share the municipal administration, with the municipality having its official address in one of the towns.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] For example, both Skillingaryd and Vaggeryd are central localities of Vaggeryd Municipality.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Conversely, there are municipalities within metropolitan areas.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] For example, there are twenty-six municipalities within the Stockholm metropolitan area.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The term "central locality" has no legal meaning and it is unclear how it should be applied to these municipalities.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Some municipalities appointing one or several localities to be the central locality.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] A residence city (Swedish: *residensstad*) is the town or city which is the political and administrative seat of the county.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] This level handles the more regional political and administrative tasks of the county, such as healthcare and public transport.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The name comes from these towns or cities being where the governor (*landshövding*) resides.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The term *chef-lieu* is applied to the capital of each Swiss canton.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In 16 of the 26 cantons, the territory is subdivided into districts.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Every district's capital is also termed a *chef-lieu* and each has a prefect.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] The term *chef-lieu* is used to designate the capital of each governorate of Tunisia.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] Each of the 24 governorates is subdivided into delegations which each have a central city as the *chef-lieu* of the delegation.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] In the United Kingdom, an administrative centre is the centre of a local authority, which is distinct from the county town of a historic county.
[src:ashburton-lakes/administrative-centre] For example, the administrative centre where the county council of Lancashire sits is Preston, even though the county town is Lancaster.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The region provides recreational opportunities including camping, sight-seeing, tramping and climbing, skiing, fishing and hunting.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] *Ōtūwharekai* / Ashburton Lakes is an area of cultural importance to the iwi Ngāi Tahu because it was a significant food-gathering area and was also on a main route for travel between Hakatere and the Rakaia trails to Te Tai Poutini.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] In 2007, the Ashburton Lakes were included in a national wetland restoration programme known as *Arawai Kākāriki*.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Monitoring of water quality in the lakes shows they are in "fair" or "poor" condition, as a result of nutrient-enrichment and sediment inflow.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] As of 2024, several of the lakes are at risk of deteriorating further into severe eutrophic states, changing from clear water with vegetation, to turbid algae-dominated water.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The Māori name *Ō Tū Wharekai* is used for the entire Ashburton Lakes district, but also as the name of two small interconnected wetlands that are commonly known as the Māori Lakes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The name builds on the Māori word *wharekai*, meaning dining or banquet hall, and signifies the importance of the area for food-gathering.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The settlement between the Crown and the rūnanga Ngāi Tahu for historic breaches of the Treaty of Waitangi included a Deed of Recognition in relation to the *Ōtūwharekai* / Ashburton Lakes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The 1998 deed acknowledges the traditional association of Ngāi Tahu with the *Ōtūwharekai* / Ashburton Lakes, including historical, cultural and spiritual aspects.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The deed requires that the Crown consult with Ngāi Tahu about changes to the management of wetland areas.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] *Ōtūwharekai*/Ashburton Lakes is an area of cultural importance to the iwi Ngāi Tahu because it was a significant food–gathering area and was also on a main route for travel between Hakatere and the Rakaia trails to Te Tai Poutini (the West Coast Region).
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The Ashburton Lakes are located in a glacial inter-montane basin between the Rangitata and Rakaia rivers that drains the eastern slopes of the Southern Alps.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] In the late Pleistocene, a combined glacier including a lobe of the Rakaia glacier, merged with the Cameron glacier and the Rangitata glacier system and reached all the way through the Ashburton Gorge to the Canterbury Plains.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Glaciation has profoundly affected the landscape, and there is evidence in the landforms of multiple glacier advances.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The last advance reached its maximum extent 28,000 years ago in the Ashburton Lakes area, and by 15,000 years ago the glaciers had retreated to the valleys of the upper Clyde and Havelock Rivers.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The lakes in the *Ōtūwharekai*/Ashburton district include Lake Camp, Lake Clearwater, Lake Emily, Lake Emma, Lake Heron, Māori Lakes, Lake Roundabout, Mystery Lake, and the Spider Lakes along with many unnamed small tarns.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Long term trends and changes in the flora in the Ashburton Lakes region can be inferred from analysis of pollen, charcoal and algae in sediment cores taken from the lakes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The analysis of sediment cores indicates that prior to the arrival of humans in the Ashburton Lakes region, there were native podocarp forests, including mataī (*Prumnopitys taxifolia)* and smaller trees such as celery pine (*Phyllocladus sp.*) around the lakes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Following human arrival, the sediment cores show a marked increase in charcoal, from large–scale burning of the vegetation.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] There is an increase in bracken fern, an early colonising plant, that is indicative of disturbance.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Following the arrival of European pastoral farmers, there was further burning of the landscape, with the result that trees were essentially removed, and replaced with a tussock and grass landscape.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] While algae have always been present in the lakes, the sediment cores show that algae has increased significantly since the arrival of humans.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The burning of tussock lands to produce young growth to feed stock has led to tall native tussocks being replaced with shorter species, and matagouri and Aciphylla species are less common.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Topdressing and oversowing has changed the vegetation, particularly at lower elevations.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Other changes are the spread of introduced and pest plants such as broom, gorse and wilding pines.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Over the period 1990 to 2010, pastoral farming in the high country stations around the lakes has become intensified, with larger herds of cattle, more fertiliser use, and winter forage grazing.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The vegetation in the stations has changed from tussock and indigenous shrubs to pasture grasses.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] This has resulted in elevated levels of phosphorus and nitrogen being discharged, increasing the levels of nutrients and sediments in the lakes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The glacial landforms, lakes and wetlands support diverse habitats and are designated in the Ashburton District Plan as Areas of Significant Nature Conservation Value.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The basin has examples of kettleholes that provide habitat for rare ephemeral turf vegetation.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The lakes, tarns and wetlands provide habitat for nationally significant and threatened species.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Environment Canterbury (ECan) has described Ōtūwharekai Lakes as "one of the few remaining areas of native biodiversity in mid-Canterbury".
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] One critically endangered species found in the area in 2024 is the Canterbury knobbled weevil.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Ashburton Lakes statistical area covers 2,995.14 km2 (1,156.43 sq mi) and had an estimated population of 110 as of June 2025, with a population density of 0.037 people per km2.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Ashburton Lakes had a population of 99 in the 2023 New Zealand census, an increase of 3 people (3.1%) since the 2018 census, and a decrease of 3 people (−2.9%) since the 2013 census.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] There were 54 males and 45 females in 54 dwellings.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The median age was 31.5 years (compared with 38.1 years nationally).
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] People could identify as more than one ethnicity.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The results were 93.9% European (Pākehā), 6.1% Māori, 3.0% Pasifika, and 12.1% other, which includes people giving their ethnicity as "New Zealander".
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] English was spoken by 93.9%, and other languages by 6.1%.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] No language could be spoken by 6.1% (e.g. too young to talk).
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The percentage of people born overseas was 6.1, compared with 28.8% nationally.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The sole religious affiliation given was 21.2% Christian.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] People who answered that they had no religion were 78.8%, and 3.0% of people did not answer the census question.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Of those at least 15 years old, 18 (22.2%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, 54 (66.7%) had a post-high school certificate or diploma, and 9 (11.1%) people exclusively held high school qualifications.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The median income was $55,800, compared with $41,500 nationally.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The employment status of those at least 15 was 60 (74.1%) full-time and 12 (14.8%) part-time.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Hakatere Conservation Park is a protected area of high country in the Ashburton Lakes district between the Rangitata and Rakaia rivers.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The park was established in 2007 and covers 680 km2 (260 sq mi) of rugged mountains and mountain basins, tussocklands and beech forest, and includes alpine and sub-alpine ecosystems, braided rivers, lakes and wetlands.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The park is a collection of discrete areas of protected conservation land, and lies within the wider Ashburton Lakes region.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The Hakatere Conservation Park is administered by the Department of Conservation.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Recreational activities within the Ashburton Lakes district include camping, sight-seeing and photography, tramping and climbing, skiing, fishing, hunting, bird-watching, horse riding and mountain biking.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The lakes provide opportunities for non-motorised boating, with power boats allowed only on Lake Camp.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] There are many places suitable for camping and picnics.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The Lake Clearwater village has around 180 private holiday home dwellings (known as cribs or baches).
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Some high-country stations in the region have established tourism ventures or accommodation on their properties.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] A project focused on restoration of the *Ō Tū Wharekai* lakes was established as part of a national programme known as *Arawai Kākāriki*.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The programme was launched in 2007 aiming for the restoration of three (subsequently five) significant wetlands.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] A case study report published by the Ministry for the Environment in 2023 reported that all the Ashburton Lakes were nutrient-enriched, with some at risk of deteriorating further into severe eutrophic states, changing from clear water with vegetation, to turbid algae-dominated water.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] None of the lakes met minimum objectives for water quality in the Land and Water Regional Plan (LWRP).
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The study reported that pastoral farming was the source for more than 90% of nutrients.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Seepage of human waste at Lake Clearwater and Lake Camp was a contributor, but represented less than 10% of the nutrient inflow.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The report found that "no systems were in place that allowed a timely response" to the decline in water quality, that the freshwater management system had failed to protect the lakes, and that too many key decisions about environmental management were delegated to farmers and their consultants.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] A former Chair of Fish & Game New Zealand stated that the health of several of the Ashburton Lakes is at serious risk and that recovery from highly eutrophic states will be costly and difficult.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] He urged ECan, the Regional Council, to take immediate action to halt the decline in water quality.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] He noted that the four high country stations in the area of the Ashburton Lakes — Lake Heron, Mt Arrowsmith, Mt Possession and Castle Ridge — had done what they believed they were allowed to do under the current ECan rules, but those rules had failed to protect the lakes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] The Environmental Defence Society called on ECan to review the Ōtūwharekai consents.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] A researcher from the Department of Public Health, University of Otago, criticised ECan, recommending that intensive winter grazing should be prohibited in the catchments, and that specific plans are required for each lake, with trigger points for action.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] Te Rūnanga o Ngāi Tahu were strongly critical of the inadequate response to earlier warnings about declining water quality and the lack of the engagement that had been promised to Ngāi Tahu as part of the 1998 Deed of Recognition.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] In 2025, owners of the main farms in the catchment areas for the Ashburton Lakes reported on studies that they had conducted, showing that the levels of nitrate in waterways on their properties typically did not increase as it passed downstream towards the lakes.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] They claimed that the focus on farmers for causing the nutrient-enrichment of the lakes was unfair.
[src:ashburton-lakes/ashburton-lakes] In 2024, the Sixth National Government announced funding for locally-led catchment groups across New Zealand, including $950,000 to the *Ōtūwharekai* / Ashburton Lakes Catchment Group, together with the Mid Canterbury Catchment Collective.
